There's a lot of good moments but all of them are interspersed with enough cheesiness that it detracts from the overall experience, and, while this may be a consequence of my own experiences with mental illness and identity, none of the identity themes landed. There was a resonance the first time it was brought up, but the more and more the same messages got repeated the more they got drained value. The character of Ezriel never worked for me, either, since they felt too much like a stock mad scientist with a tragic backstory attached that I couldn't get invested in them. His behavior being tolerated for so long also breaks my suspension of disbelief for what I imagine the Foundation would let fly with their researchers.

It's not a bad article, but there's a lot that detracts from it being a truly powerful experience.

-1.







